title: Sony X1000V Filter Clip on V2

description.text:
In progress print of a clip on filter for a Sony X1000V camera. Works by using the little grooves on top and below the lens to clip on. Will work with any sony action cameras that have those ridges.

I haven't tested this yet printing, I'll update it when i get it printed and on the camera.

The idea here is that you could use a hobby knife to cut out some cheapo cheap amazon special DSLR lens covers and glue them to the front of this and use them for the Sony. Filters that might be nice include UV, Polarized, ND filters, or even just Skylight filters to protect the lens.

I imagine for now that you'll want to either print this very slowly or with supports to avoid warping those clips. I only have PLA available right now so I'll give it a go with that, but will update later with more information.

UPDATE:
V1 was a failure, but i have now uploaded V2, which WORKS. No idea how long it will take clipping and unclipping, as I know PLA fatigues pretty easily, but hopefully it'll be worth the 20 cents it cost to make one.

Updates to V2:

Clippy parts are now shorter, farther part, and curved to reflect the curvature of the camera.
Small supporting structures were added to the sides to prevent wobble (which are actually unnecessary i think).
More fillets to make it print while facing down with CURA, just add like 5% filled support.

description.text:
The clamping mechanism I designed to support the wiring bundle on my 3D printer wasn't holding up, so I designed this upgraded bundle clamp.

The clamp comes in 3 diameters - 14, 18, and 20 mm to hold a range of bundle sizes. I found I needed a narrower base in another application so there are also 2 different base sizes. The standard base width is 18mm while the narrower base is 14mm wide. Unless you need the narrow base the standard base is recommended.

The STEP files are included for the standard base sizes.

STLs are oriented in best printing position. The flange will print better on its side rather than an upside down U.

There are STLs for both the standard and narrow bracket mounts but only one flange STL for each size. They are interchangeable.

The base hole diameter is 5mm and the clamp uses M3 hardware. To keep it simple I didn't design nut traps. Just use the M3 bolts to cut threads into the plastic. Even with pulling on the cable bundle the clamp will have sufficient holding force.

This thing is part of a final project for CPSC 183 Technology and the Law with Prof. Brad Rosen at Yale University. The idea of this project is to ask friends for ideas for physical objects that they would like to have that could be printed on the Makerbot TOM. I have designed them, printed them out and given them to the people who requested them. I also have uploaded them here to Thingiverse to add to the library of physical objects that people find cool, useful, or just plain fun!

Print and clean. I used a Dremel plastic cutting bit to clean out the support structure underneath the tabs. A little sanding here and there and it should fit together perfectly! Don't forget you also need a 1"x1.5"x.25" piece of plexiglass (or a little smaller than that) to protect the photo!

As I'm still using the WanHao plaster on my heated bed, the glass is a little too high for me to use the original glass bed clamps. So I made some modifications to the clamps so that the screws can secure the glass from moving around on the bed.

Also, this remix has a thicker base to possibly reduce any warp? Anyway, I've printed and using the set of 4 clamps on my 3D printer.

The holes are supposed to accommodate M3 screws and M3 nut, but I had to drill with a M3 drill bit in order to have the screws move nicely in the hole.

Anyway, the clamps seems to work nicely. :)

28th March 2016:
Update - If you are printing a long job, this clamp doesn't work as the screws will become loose and the glass will move a bit causing distortions to the thing. Best to switch to the old paper clip or alternative solutions like these:

title: Pieces parts for a Slide bolt

description.text:
Yet again some project around the house has prompted a 3d Printed solution.  
Needed a slide bolt to fix a swinging gate style garage door.  I had a perfect piece of plastic to make the rod (rectangle 20mm x 25mm).  But, didn't have any of the other hardware to make a complete slide bolt.  Also, didn't feel like spending  an money at the home goodies outlet giant.  So, here are some pieces to complete the slide bolt.  
There is a guide piece that can be printed as many times as necessary to create a useful sliding path.  Also, this is used as the top of the door frame latch catch.  
The end piece is just a piece to keep the bolt from hitting the ground since I have this one mounted vertically.  
There is a 2 part track and slider to be used to hold the bolt in its locked position or moved out of the way to allow the bolt to hit the lower stop and be in its unlocked position.  
I know this description doesn't do it justice.  Sorry.  But I'm sure that there are a couple of people who know exactly what this is.  To those, I hope it helps.

title: Sub Miniature Micro Switch, Limit Switch

description.text: I needed some limit switches for a project but didn't want to spend the $3-7 each that these things cost from Honeywell, etc. so I made my own using standard 6x6mm tactile switches. Buy the switches in bulk like I did and these will cost you about $0.05 each. Sure they're not the same level as the Honeywell but they'll get the job done. Example tactile switches: http://goo.gl/ALffCi Photo shows three that I made next to a Honeywell that I typically use. I soldered the leads after I glued the switches in so the solder job isn't the best. In the future I'll solder before I install the switch. Note also that the dimensions on this may vary a bit printer to printer based on calibration. This is tuned for my printer, obviously, so you may need to tweak the file, or use some XActo action to get it dialed in for your situation. It's pretty close though and we're really only talking about, give or take, 1/2-1/4mm here or there. These are pretty small.

description.text:
Most likely my final iteration of this frame for the jjrc h6c.This frame was built for performance. Main frame sliced in cura, 0.2 layer height, 16 percent infill, .4 height for top and bottom layers (+/- affects screw hole rigidity). Other parts printed at 50-100 percent infill. No raft or supports needed if printed in the right orientation.

Main frame has it's rigidity focused in the x axis, also z with stepped surface I-beam design, while lower frame and I-beam brace are in the y axis. Foot is .8mm thick for reduced weight. mbrace part can be used in place of lower cambrace part, for detaching camera for reduced weight.

Added the camera mount. Take care not to bend the flat flex connector as these are delicate. Board can be tricky to insert into cage, and should only be inserted in one orientation (from the top), then the frame bent a bit to snap it in gently.

Edit: Getting rolling shutter effect with the camera mount. Not sure how to get rid of this, perhaps printing the frame with less or different infill percentage will give a different resonant point to get it out of sync with camera fps, also camera fps increases as the aperture reduces. Only getting rse with small aperture in bright condions.

title: Peace Contest Gravity Water Filter Coupler

description.text:
24/7 some one is desperate for clean safe drinking water for little to no cost. With sterilized sand, charcoal, pop bottles and a coupler you can make potable water. This is a device that allows one to use two used beverage bottles as a gravity water filter. The coupler solves the problem of leakage between the connection of two bottles when one bottle is coupled upside down, and on top of a second bottle. A water tight seal is required. The anti-leaking is accomplished with the addition of a simple angled (wedge) surface located at the middle of the coupler. The rim of the bottle compresses into the wedge and forms a waterproof seal. edit: 9/3/13 update added PCO1881 Closure. This design attempts to meet the ISBT standards, Finish No. PCO-1881-0. This is the most widely used pop bottle thread. I included a "Stash Plug" to seal the coupler. Inside the plug is a small pocket with an 1 mm O-ring grove. I will add the cover when it's finished. I may change the stash ring, and eliminate the O-ring in favor of a snap fit. I added a small eating fork to the end of the Stash Carry Ring. The fork stores inside of the pop bottle neck. Spoon, and knife to follow. I will redesign these to improve the function, ease of printing, and robustness. Adding simple utilitarian devices to the gravity water filter coupler will make the coupler more valuable to the user. Being of more value, it will be stored in a more memorable location, and in times of a disaster it's location will more easily be recalled. There is a small lanyard loop which allow you to attach the bottle to the coupler so you don't loose it. The lanyard loop is also useful as a key ring bob, and it's small size makes it easy to always carry it with you. The exterior is fluted to allow soft water soaked hands to obtain a confident hold of the coupler. The part is designed for 3d printing with one end rounded, and the other end flat. A flat is naturally formed on the outside wall of the closure to provide clearance for the lanyard. The flat area can be used for identification. It can be marked with a pen, a scribe, or with the tip of a solder gun. The coupler is printed in a bright color like yellow or orange so it's easy to find if it's dropped. I envision the gravity fed water filter being used unattended. Unattended water filtration requires a reliable, and rugged coupler to prevent water from leaking. A threaded coupler was chosen over competing options such as an internal plug because it won't fall apart. A straight walled plug inserted into the inside diameter of the bottle opening would be a precarious connection. This is due to the finish of the neck of the bottle being a reverse taper. A straight walled plug coupler would tend to creep out over time, this would cause a spill of a valuable resource. Tubing placed over the outside diameter of the bottle threads would most likely leak immediately. A threaded coupler provides a reliable leak proof connection, and a universally understood means of attachment (a plastic bottle thread). It might be possible to make a cold cast (plastic casting resin) of the coupler for a moderate sized production run. If there is interest in this I can modify the internal thread, and the exterior to have draft to help release a cold cast part from a mold. "Designs should advance, directly or indirectly, the safety, wellbeing, and performance of all people" The gravity fed water filter promotes safety and wellbeing when used as an emergency water filter in a disaster area. Having a supply of sanitized water promotes peace by removing the fear of not having a source of clean drinking water. Instructions:
Collect two pop bottles.
Cut the bottom off of one of the bottles.
Connect the two bottles together with the coupler.
Fill the upper bottle half full with charcoal.
Fill the remaining half with sand.
Place a piece of cloth over the sand to act as a pre-filter.
Pour water in and wait for it to filter through. To prepare the sand:
Bake the sand in an oven at 250 F, for 3 hours. To prepare the charcoal:
Place the charcoal in a sock and pound until it is a powder.
You want the water to flow through the charcoal, not around it. In disaster areas instructions could be posted in key locations, and broadcast over the radio of how to make a gravity water filter. I've left the design open due to the varied bottle threads that are available. I will include two of the more popular bottle closure styles the PCO1881, and the PCO1810. The thread that I have drawn presently was measured from a common bottle, but may not fit all styles of threads. I plan to investigate if I'm able to integrate multiple thread forms into one generic thread profile. Edit:
After reviewing my original design (Gravity_Water_Filter_Coupler_v1.stl) to the PCO1881 closure (thread) I discovered that the length of the bottle neck, compared to the depth of the sealing surface within the closure leaves minimal room for over tightening. The overall length needs to be shorten to provide clearance. I have provided a new drawing that follows the PCO1881 standard. I'm deleting my original drawing to avoid confusion. Link to CAD drawings (.pdf) of bottle cap closure: PCO1881
http://imajeenyus.com/mechanical/20120508_bottle_top_threads/28mm-ISBT-PCO-1881-Finish-3784253-17.pdf PCO1810
http://imajeenyus.com/mechanical/20120508_bottle_top_threads/pco1810.pdf Attribution:
There are thousands of references to gravity fed water filters.
I'm unsure of the original source of this idea. I would like your feed back to further improve the coupler design. For example should I add a raised boss to the center of the coupler. A raised boss would allow creating a 3-way connection. Print the coupler and assemble it on different bottles, and tell me what you discover. Please send me a private message (PM) if you feel it will be a distraction in the comments area..
Thank you!!!

description.text:
The Philips Hue wireless dimmer replaces the wired light switches used by ordinary bulbs when you replace these with Philips Hue lights. For some unknown and completely mysterious reason Philips decided to make the base place of the dimmer slightly narrower than the standard width of European light switches. The "normal" width of these is 84x84 mm with a hole width of 60 mm. If you just remove the existing light switch and fasten the dimmer using double sided tape, the result will be very visible marks from the old 84 mm switch. This is naturally completely unacceptable.
Another problem is that the dimmer is higher than 84mm, so the normal cover plates for electrical mounts are useless as a base for mounting the dimmer.

This design is for a plate that can be fastened to a standard light switch mount with standard screws and then serves as a perfect base for attaching the Hue dimmer plate. The result looks pretty nice.
Using the bottom of the print as outer surface produces the best results. You have to manually countersink the holes for the mounting screws with a small file or a drill.

The plate is available in two versions: One with just two holes in the middle. This works if the electricians mounted the switch holder in the standard way. The other version has a plethora of holes that make it possible to mount the switch rotated or in any of three different heights, while still completely covering up the old mount.

The original FreeCAD drawing as well as the printable STL files are available for download.

You want to print with a high infill level, say 75%. Otherwise the plates will bend in the middle when you tighten them down with the mounting screws. You can print with coarse settings (0.3mm) and high speed since only the base of the print is visible. I pushed it a bit to far on the multi hole plate in the picture, which I printed at the absolute maximum speed for my printer. This produced uneven holes and crap on the border.

description.text:
I tried several extruders, and even built my own, but the Airtripper is still my favorite: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:126778

The only weakness is its weakness, the walls are slightly too thin. When printing with high speeds (150mm/s), the extruder bends, which makes much more bending problems like a 1m long bowden tube. PLA is much stiffer then ABS, so i printed the extruder with PLA, but the filament sticked in the extruder because PLA gets so fast hot from friction. The simple solution was, to make the holes bigger, now you can put 4mm PTFE bowden tubes into the holes. Simply secure with a few drops superglue, its much easyer then the nut-fixed version, and you can remove the PTFE anytime with a bit force, PTFE is very glue resistent.

The Airtripper is a stiff and material saving design, perfect for multi-material printers and every printer at all, just keep the bowden as short as possible, retract speed 150-300mm/s, retract acceleration 10.000-15.000mm/s², 3mm retract with 30cm bowden length, ~7mm with 1m bowden length.

If you didnt know: You can change the output side of the extruder in your slic3r, right klick on the loaded airtripper_kolbi.stl and choose "flip along axis".

description.text:
OK, most kinks seem to be worked out. I would still suggest TPU, but will work with hard filament like PLA. Pictures are printed with hatchbox glow in the dark PLA. Cleanest print with front facing up and tabs down to print bed with support. Please remove support carefully as to not damage the tabs. Easiest print is face down tabs up.....giggity. Its just difficult to remove the support material without some junk being left, but the tabs are able to maintain their integrity.
My suggestion for best figment with PLA would be to snap tabs on right (button) side, then tabs on antenna side. Push door right carefully to allow left tabs to be secured.

Special thanks to spmahoney78, he has the UBAD module and has given much needed feedback and countless feet of filament test printing and fitting. It still is not 100%, but it's better than nothing, and free.

Buy me a beer? PayPal is [email protected]

comments.text: I tried printing in PETG a couple of different orientations and it's so thin it breaks at the weak points when trying to install.  I think the clips are too big and the cutout for the screen is too low.  have you thought about making the faceplate thicker maybe just .35mm for some additional strength and adding a brace inside running vertical along the left and right sides of the screen. I tried removing the tabs for the clips completely and it was a much better fit. Thank you for creating this thing, I'll post pics of my attempts.

comments.text: What infill are you using?  I have not had an issue with cracking. I can raise the screen, and cut down the tabs no issue. I uploaded at test file for you.  We can work together to get it right. I am printing the  new file on my end now.

I drew these Minecraft figures up in December 2012 to give some young Minecraft and chess fans for Christmas, and finally got around to fixing up the models for Thingiverse!  
Mostly pixel-by-pixel representations  of characters from the game Minecraft by Mojang, who owns them. A few very small modifications were made to reduce bridging, and feet were added to improve stability.   
The theme for this set is Overworld Mobs. The same piece is used twice for the king and queen. To tell them apart, you can replace one of the Endermen heads with a Pumpkin head.  
Print each team in one color if they will be used for playing chess. When scaled up 1.5, they make great toys for toddlers.

Most pieces are printed in two parts; the head snaps on to the body after printing. I decided that a little too tight was preferable to a little too loose. Place the head upside down on a hard surface, and firmly push the body down to snap it into place. Clean up with a knife as needed.  
Print each team in one color if they will be used for playing chess.  
When sized up 150 percent, the pieces make great toys for younger children.

title: Pegboard Tool Holder Template (Base) For Derivatives

description.text:
This is a solid base with side clips that can be used to make various tool holders. My purpose was to design a pegboard holder that could print easily without rafts and without any support material. Fits 1/4 inch pegboard holes at 1 inch interval separation.

The base is a solid block of plastic with side protrusions that "snap" into two side pieces which are printed separately from the base.

To use this base for your own project, you need to include the module in your project. The module takes a single argument, which is the width in inches (must be an integer if the project is going to fit on standard pegboard). Simply design the tool holes you want in the base using openscad and combine the two with a difference call. I have included an example using an array of hexagonal holes to make a holder for little hex bits.

There is a second module in the base file called baseDeep which makes a deeper (ie extends further inferior) base. I haven't used this yet, but it might be nice for having angled tool holes that come out the front.

If you just want to print the hex holder in the picture, all you need are the example.stl and side.stl files. The ".scad" and "base" files are for making your own tool holders in openscad.
